Current Problems

God Object Anti-pattern: The Processor struct is doing everything - downloading, caching, progress tracking, result formatting, and error handling
Mixed Abstraction Levels: Low-level operations (mutex locks, channel management) mixed with high-level business logic
Poor Separation of Concerns: UI/presentation logic (tables, colors) mixed with core processing logic
Unclear Data Flow: Results flow through channels, then get mutated, then formatted - hard to follow
Inconsistent Error Handling: Some errors stop processing, others get collected, some get formatted differently

Refactoring Plan
Phase 1: Extract Core Concepts
Create these new packages/types:

internal/runner - Handles the actual execution of tool operations

Runner interface with methods like Run(tool *tool.Tool) Result
Separate implementations for different operations (download, status check, etc.)


internal/results - Manages result collection and aggregation

Collector type that safely collects results from concurrent operations
Summary type that provides aggregated view of all results


internal/presentation - All UI/formatting logic

TableFormatter for table rendering
ErrorFormatter for error message formatting
Keep all color/styling decisions here



Phase 2: Refactor the Processor
Transform Processor into a thin orchestrator:
gotype Processor struct {
    runner   runner.Runner
    results  results.Collector
    cache    cache.Manager  // Extract cache operations to interface
    progress progress.Manager
}

func (p *Processor) Process(tools tools.Tools, tags tags.IncludeTags) error {
    // 1. Setup
    ctx := context.Background()

    // 2. Process tools concurrently
    g, ctx := errgroup.WithContext(ctx)
    g.SetLimit(p.config.Parallel)

    for _, tool := range tools {
        tool := tool // capture
        g.Go(func() error {
            result := p.runner.Run(ctx, tool)
            p.results.Add(result)
            return nil
        })
    }

    // 3. Wait and collect
    g.Wait()

    // 4. Return summary
    summary := p.results.Summary()
    if summary.HasErrors() {
        return summary.Error()
    }
    return nil
}
